‘ Ah, make the most of what remains to spend‚ , Before we too into the Dust descend, Dust unto Dust, and under Dust to lie, Sans Wine, sans Song, sans Singer, and—sans End.’

But Lucretius does not believe that the only serious business of life is sensual pleasure, and will not say, ⁶ Let us eat and drink, for to-morrow we die! To his austere and noble nature this argument made no appeal, and he only mentions it to dismiss it with contempt ².

⁴What then does Lucretius say? He can promise no heaven hereafter3 but he tells men that if they have nothing to hope, they have also nothing to fear, beyond the grave.

It cannot be doubted that in the life-time of Lucretius the great majority of his countrymen believed in some form of future existence³. Nor was this belief confined to the simple and ignorant.
